{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_jamaica_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039314/1908032201/0409.xml":{"full_text":"WWW.YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, SUNDA}\nCe EEu\nhiding for the legalizing of traffic agreements\nage, Wm Tre Ye LT\nfor the legalizing of traffic agreements\neen railroads. He called attention to the\nthat labor organizations had been ex\n\u00a2t\ned to agree to such legislation in return\na provision exempting them from the opera\nor\nof the law. The legislators present were\not ready to assent to the demands made bY\nber in the bill of grievances recently sub\nitted to Congress, and on that account urged\nt it would be inadvisable to attempt any\nof the Sherman jaw at this time. It\nsai@ that the President, while not -actually\njon\nLi it, was not disposed to agree with\nhe advice given to him. He declared that it\nas but justice to the railroads to permit traf\nagreements under proper restrictions and\nnirol by the Interstate Commerce Commission,\nnd said that no interests would be injured\nv such legislation. He was not impressed by\nhe statement made to him that labor would\n\u2018yegard this as extending benefits to railroads\nwnd withholding them from unions.\nThe President was told that such a course\nimt this time would be bad pelitics for the ma\n\u2018ority party to play. On the statement that it\n\u201cwas mot certain that labor had unalterably re\nSected the proposals for an agreement under\ni which some of the henefits would accrue 1p or\nized labor. the subject went over until the\ncident ie ready to present his bill in con\nform. Messrs. Aldrich, Dalzell and Pavne\nd that they might be of a different opinion on\ning the bill.\nberete\nRepresentative Hepburn discussed with the\ndent the terms of the bill amending the\n\u201ctrust law. as it has been modified since\nbor's attitude became hostile to the general\nheme urged by the Civic Federation. Mr.\nepburn will introduce the bill in the House,\nbebly on Monday.\nSonn after the conference ended a prominent\nYew England Republican Senator who talked\nth the President said that a child labor blll\night be added to the list. He also expressed\nhe belief that Congress might fail to pass the\nti-insunction and Sherman law revision bills.\nNHUGHES MASS MEETING AT ALBANY.\nWWational League Plans State Campaign-\u2014\nF War in Enemy's Country.\ni By Telegraph to The Tribune.\nAlbany, March 21.\u2014A mass meeting under the di\ndon of the Hughes League of the United States\n$rere next Thursday has been announced. General\nWoodford. Seth Low, Congressman Wilson and\nPresident Young of the Republican Club are ex\nected to speak. A long list of officers of the\nng, including many well known men here,\nas Deen prepared. This in a sense fs carrying\na war into the enemy's country. since William\nWarnes, jr.. leader of Albany County, maintains\nusly that i{ughes cannot possibly be nomi\nand has seid that the delegates from this\nCongress district would not be instructed for him.\nSimilar mestings will be held in other parts of\nstate\nnated\nhe\nbe RK ANSAS REJECTED TAFT AMENDMENT\nIRyv Telecraph to T\n{By Telegraph lo 20 imhulk.l\nLittle Rock, Ark., March 21.\u2014It developed to-day\nt last might the Republican State Committee\nsejected resolutions favoring instructions for Taft.\n\u201cWhen the resolution committee submitted its re\npersonally\u2019 favoring Secretary Taft for the\nepublican nomination, Frank M. Thompson, of\nHope, offered the following amendment:\nWe pledge him our loyal ana earnest support,\ncommend to our Republican friends through\nArkansas the plan of ign] their dele\ntes to vote for William H. Taft until he i= nomi\nted by the Chicago conventiin.\nThe amendment was defeated, only three votes\ning cast for it. The original resolutions wers\nhen adonted.\nut\ng\nSENECA INSTRUCTS FOR HUGHES.\nInterlaken. N. Y., March Zi.\u2014Delegates 10 1he\n\u00a31ate Republican Convention elected to-day by the\n Eoneca county convention were instructed to use\nevery endeavor to secure the election of delegates\n10 the national convention favoring the nomination\nof Governor Hughes for President.\nI\n\u00ab0TH DISTRICT TO INDORSE HUGHES.\nThe Republicans of the i0th Assembly District\n&ill hold a meeting if! the rooms of the Charles E.\nBiughes League. Ne.-231 East 16th strect, tomor\nyow evening and will pass resolutions indorsing\nGovernor Hughes for President. The speakers will\nte Frank Hendrick, Michael A. Hines and others.\nNEW JERSEY DEMOCRATS TO SET DATES.\n\nA \u00aball for a meeting of the Democratic State\nCommitiee of New Jersey in the Davidson Build\ngng. at Washingten and Montgomery streets, Jer\nsey City, on March 26 was jessued by Robert S.\nSiudspeth, its ehzirman, in Jersey City yesterday.\nfThe committee will fix dates for the primaries\nfor the election of delegates to ithe convention to\nFelect delegates to the national convention and will\n&et 2 date for the state convention.\nrONNERS SEES COUNTY LEADERS.\nAlbany, March Il \u2014Chairman Conners ol ihe\ncratic State Committee left for Buffalo\nhis afternoon, afier a twenty-four hour visit to\n $emocratic state headquarters here. During his\nay he had conferences with the Democratic\ngounty chairmen or other representatives of the\nP v organizations in the ceunties of Clinton, Co\numbia, Bssex, Fulton-Hamilton, Herkimer, Mont\n4 rv, Oneida, Orleans, Oswego, Otsegn, Rensso\n$zer. Saratoga, SchenectadX, Schoharie, Warren and\nWashington. Mr. Conners discussed the political\ntuation generally, but hed nothing to say for\n\n\n\nblication.\nThe Weber\nIs The Piano\nOf The Opera\nMme. CAVALIERI\nof the Conried Metropolitan Opera Company\nwrites:\nThe WEBER PIANO CO. New York:\nGentlemen\u2014The human voice seems to\nbe the standard by which other musical\ninstruments are judged. 1 know that one\nof the first exclamations hear when\nplay mv Weber Piano for any one is:\n\u201cWhat a beautiful singing tone!\u201d\nAnd it 1= true. I know of no other\nplano that possesses this quality to such\na wonderful degree\u2014that harmonizes so\nbeautifully with the voice or that has\nsuch sustaining and carrying powers.\nThe Weber has indeed a most exquisite\nsinging tone,\nBi EL\nLINA CAVALIERI.\nThe AEOLIAN (CO.\nAon\nAFCOLIAN HALL\n262 Fifth Ave., near 34th St.\nNEW YORK\nThe Weber\nIs The Piano\nOf The Opera\nof the Conried Metropolitan Opera Company\nwrites:\nJOWA SOCIETY DINNER\nTOWA SOCIETY DINNER\nTWO GOVERNORS SPEAK.\n\nTWO GOVERNORS SPEAK.\nMore than 225 Hawkeyes and Guests\nHear Hughes and Cummins.\nGovernor Hughes spoke to the Towa Society at\nthe Hotel Plaza last night on the duties of citi\nzenship, but he came to that part of his ad\ndress after he had welcomed Iowa's Governor,\nAlbert B. Cummins, to the state, expressing the\nhope that the citizens of that commonwealth\nwho had come to this city to enjoy its blessings\nhad not lost the virtues of their home soil. He\nexhorted the Iowans not to give their first atten\ntion to national affairs. The city should come\nfirst in their thoughts, he said, and added that\nin this city are the greatest problems to be\nsolved.\n\u201cBe not so earnest in chasing the dollar,\u201d he\nurged, \u201cthat you forget to help your fellow men.\u201d\nThis sentiment was warmly cheered. And when\nhe said that in the fight for right it did not\nmatter who was on the other side, the people\ncould and would win for righteousness, there\ncame a burst of applause that had the ring of\nA ET ET iT NE TTT TN ee\nPIT HH HH HH HH HH HHH TH NH HT I I Cn re op Tn OE TN 10 Td dr Se of eat\nft SRA AR 8 RR Sh dni.\naes od _- Aud hy\nthe West in it.\nWhen Governor Hughes was introduced bY\nGeneral Grenville M. Dodge, the president of the\nsociety, the welcome was =0 tumultuous that it\nwas severs! minutes before he could speak. Then\nhe said:\nThis is one of the happy bufdend of New\nYork. 1 am not here for a speech, but to join\nyou in a welcome to vour Governor, who is here\nin an agreeable and extra-territorial jurisdiction.\nThe hours of a governor are given over to con\nsideration, exhortation and felicitation. To\nnight 1 have been felicitatihg the naval militia\nin Brooklyn over the opening of an armory of\nwhich 4hey have cause to be proud\u2014a naval\nmilitia, indeed, of which I fear all citizens know\nfar too little and ought to know much, giving,\nas 1 believe it did, fourteen commanders of ships\nin the Spanish war and one thousand enlisted\nmen.\niI now come io felicitate the citizens of New\nYork who were once citizens of lowa. 1 trast\nthat these citizens have not departed from the\nvirtue of their native soil. Some people have a\nstrange idea of New York. It can readily .e\nbelieved that all of the villanies that are sald\nto be committed in this state are not all com\nmitted by the native born.\nIt is a pleasant thing to meet with these state\nsocieties. They keep alive the interest in the old\nhome. This state pride is a splendid thing. There\nis in us an excess and an exuberance of patriotism\nthat cannot expend itself in the state of one\u2019s ac\ntivities, but must find expression in the affection\nfor the state of one\u2019s birth.\nNew York seems to gather together the best of\nall states, of all nations. We have here the heav\njest of all problems to solve. How glad 1 would\nhe to attend here in New York a dinner of New\nYorkers. 1 have attended Welsh dinners, Irish\ndinners, German dinnegs, dinners of sons of all\nstates, sons of other lands, but it is only when 1\nmeet these leagues, these societies, that 1 meet\nNew Yorkers. They are all New Yorkers when\nthey conie to tell the executive about his duties.\nThere was a lot of laughter at this sally. The\nGovernor then said that they were all New\nYorkers, he was a New Yorker, an upstate New\nYorker, of which he could boast as well as\nthose who claimed birth in far distant states.\nContinuing, he said:\nAll the city of New York, all the State of New\nYork, offer of good and bad are simply the marks\nof American progress. We are here the clearing\nhouse of the American nation. Here are focussed\nall the activities of the American people. Here\nare all men of power and supernal ambition. They\ncome here seeking opportunities. But it may be\nsometimes feared they do not always recognize\nthe limits that should be set te their own oppor\ntunities in order that the opportunities 0f- others\nmay be fully realized. All are seeking a chance.\nConseaguently here we have wide examples of vir\ntue, excesses of vice, extremes of ambition, acmes\nof attainment.\nBut I believe there is no place in the world\nwhere we will find more honest ambition than riglit\nhere in this city of New York. Nor more intel\nligent effort, nor mare sincere devotion to Amer\nJoan ideals than right here in the Empire State\nand eity.\nNow it i= a great mistake to believe that in New\nYork human nature ic different from human nature\nin Des Moines, Cedar Rapids or Burlington. What\nmen do and will do is bound more by ambition\nthan by state of origin. There is just as much\nreason to teach the Ten Commandments to the boy\nfrom Towa who comes to New York as there is to\nthe boy from Schoharie County or from New York\niteelf. We understand each other a littie better\nby these constant interchanges of good fedling.\nThe men from lowa know the men from New York\nbetter.\nThe men of Iowa who go back to Towa, if they\nsay truly when thev go back. will say that here\nmm New York is simply the city of endeavor, ambi\ntion, enterprise and energy. It is not New York.\njt is the United States in New York that makes\nNew York.\nThen the Governor spoke of the vast foreign\npopulations here, Irish, Germans and Italians\nand others, all good American citizens in the\nmaking. He went on:\nIt is perhaps a truism that New Yorkers do nou\nknow New York. The Wall Street man leaves lis\nbusiness, journeys uptown in a e\u00a2ar or train, or\nperhaps walks up Broadway, stops in at his club\nand goes home to dinner. He does not know New\nYork. his city. And vet that is what thousands do.\nNew York is changing constantly, from day te day,\nand the conditions that mark our progress are\nbeing studied with very little intelligence.\nHe urged his hearers tg go over to the Ameri\ncan Museum of Natural History and study there\nthe problem shown by the city congestion ex\nhihit. The Governor continued:\nGo there and learn that there are the greatest\nproblems we are facing in this coun:ry. Right her\nis the test of our patriotism. l.et it be understood\nthat no man should graprle wiih the problems of\nthe nation i* he does not first grapple with ihe\nproblems which lie at his own dogr. It is up to\nyou. It is up to all of us. Don\u2019t try to escape\nresponsibility for these things upon any ground of\ndistant birth. Don\u2019t be so earnest in chasing the\nalmighty dollar that you forget to heip vour fellow\nnian.\ni don\u2019t think the average American is much of a\n\nCAT ADT TATIY TRIBUNE. SUNDAY, MARCH 22, 1908.\nHW. YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, SUNDAY, MARCH 22, 1908.\nA\nprovince.\u2019 1 don\u2019t believe in the enmity 1 hear of\nin the West as existing toward New York. You\nmeet a man upon the boulevards of Faris, in Rotten\nRow in London, in Unter den Linden in Berlin,\nand if he is from America he will begin at once to\ntalk about New York, and, like as not, tell you\nthat he lives there. 1 am not so sure that if you\njook him up vou will mot find that he is not regis\ntered from New York.\nGovernment in these days is a very compli\ncated thing. A good many things pave to have\nattention\u2014and the one thing to b& dene is to\nshow that the people still run the country. in\nany fight that may come up {it doesn\u2019t make\nany difference who is on ithe other side; the\npeople will win out in the end. You have to give\nconsideration to the motives of men, the ideals\nof the men who exercise the great power of\nenforcing the popular will, when you chose them.\nI.et the people's will be enferced by men who\nare not (rving tc play games, but who are\ntrying to do what the people want them to do,\nand who strive to do their duty.\nLet us sec to it that when the government\ntouches a subject it will be touched not for\npolitical purposes, but because it is right and is\na desirable thing. Let us insist that any man\nin official asmthority shall recognize a sacred\nobligation. in any department of life a man\nwho attempts a judiciary obligation should per\nform that obligation, whether he comes from\nlowa. Pennsylvania or any other\u00aestate in the\nUnion.\nWhen Governor Cummins arose to speak he\nsaid: \u201cRemembering the awful retribution which\nso swiftly foilowed the \u2018Fairbanks cocktail,\u201d I\nask vou to rise and drink with mein water\u2014if\nthere is such a fluid here\u2014to the health and\nprosperity of Charles E. Hughes, Governor of\nthe State of New York.\u201d He then proposed an\nother toast, to *\u2018the commander of armies, the\nconstructor of railways, the patriotic citizen, the\npresident of your society, General Granville M.\nDodge.\u201d\nThe speech of Iowa's Governor was largely a\ndefence of the attitude of Iowa toward eco\nnomics and political subjects that have been en\ngrossing tha attention of the nation. After in\nsisting that the people of his state were not re\nsponsible for the recent panic, Governor Cum\nmins said:\nWe applauded Charles E. Hughes as he laid bare\nthe wickedness of men charged with the most\nsacred trust that can be committed to mortal\nhands. We cheered another eminent son of New\nYork as he boldly struck out through an unexplored\nwilderness of statesmanship, guided only by the\ncompass of conscience, and we are cheering him\nstill. Our people never tire in their acclaim. All\nhail to Theodore Roosevelt! It is sald that he\nhas made mistakes: I suppose he has, but the mis\ntakes of a man who is trying to find the safe path\nare better than the inaction of a man who shrinks\naway, saving \u2018\u2018there is no path\u2014let us be content\nas we are.\u201d It is said that he talks too much: it\nmay be so, but I would rather hear the voice of a\nman declaring what he believes to be true, even\nif he is wrong. than to listen to the platitudes of\nthe man who is too cowardly or too conservative\nto say anything.\nGovgrnor Cummins took up the trust question,\nsaying the people of Iowa cared not how large\na corporation may become if it is built up\nthrough superior sagtcity, but added that if\n\u201cpirates of industry\u201d deliberately entered into a\nconspiracy to stifle existing and prevent future\ncompetition, he believed they ought to \u201cexpiate\ntheir crimes in the disagreeable way well known\nto common malefactors.\u201d Then he told of Iowa\nlegislation directed ainst corporations,\nThe Governor, in closing, asked that the re\nsponsibility for the recent financial troubles be\nnot placed on Iowa and endeavored to point out\nthe real cause, when he said:\nLook rather to a system which has permitted\nreckless men to flood the country and its markets\nwith worthless and baseless stocks and in\nadequately protected bonds: look rather to a sys\ntemi which In our stock exchanges makes one-half\nthe members implacable enemies of every corpora\ntion whose stocks are listea for purchase or sale:\nlook rather to a system of banking which at the\nvery moinent when banks are most needed compels\nthem to susperd their most important functions;\nand above all and beyond all, look at the spirit\nwhich has repudiated the eternal and in the end\noverpowering truth that stable permanent wealth\ncan be produced only by honest faithful labor.\nin opening the speaking General Dodge pro\nposed a toast to President Roosevelt, who, he\nsaid, was ranked in lowa as on a level with\nWashington, Lincoln, Grant and McKinley. He\ncalled for three cheers and a tiger. which were\ngiven standing, with waving of napkins.\nBefore Governor Hughes addressed the so\nciety Representative Frank O. Lowden, of 1lli\nnois, spoke on \u201cThe Birth of a Race\u201d; J. B. Sul\nlivan, who opposed Governayr Cpmmins as the\nDemocratic candidate at the last election, on\n\u201clowa, Her Influence\u201d; Judge John F. Dillon\non \u201clowa\u2019s Contribution to Our National Juris\nprudence\u201d and Senator Dolliver on \u201cThe Ideal\nFarming Community.\u201d Each paid particular\ntributes to Iowa, although Representative Low\nden upheld the claims of Illinois to considera\ntion,\na A\nat Tt,\nCopyright by Alm\u00e9 Dupont.\nDr. Lyon\u2019s\nPERFECT\nTooth Powder\nCleanses, preserves and beautifies the teeth\n\u2014an purifies the breath\nA superior dentifrice for people of refinement\nEstablished in 1866 by\n54 Lp. ADS.\nA ote nr.\nHUGHES THE OPTIMIST\nHUGHES THE OPTIMIST\nMEN NINE-TENTHS GOOD.\nMEN NINE-TENTHS GOOD.\nMean Well and Most of Them Do It,\nHe Tells Beta Theta Pts.\nJ TH I EE TT EH EE ET A  N _\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 SU \u2014_\u2014 A _\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 i EE 4 _\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 EE; \u2014\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014_ A \u2014_\u2014\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014  _\u2014\u2014 ECR\n\nGovernor Hughes expressed his faith in hu\nman nature to three hundred members of Beta\nTheta Pi at the Hotel Astor last night by say\ning that nine hundred out of every thousand\n\u2018men meant to do right, and that most of them\ndid do so. \u201cIf it were not so this great com\nmonwealth would never have attained its pres\nent supremacy,\u201d said the Governor. We are\nhuman. and these feliows must see that they do\nnot overstep the bounds. Even men who come\nfrom Towa and Kansas must be watched as\nclosely as if they were from here. The Ameri\ncan people stand for equal rights for all and spe\ncial privileges for none.\u201d\n\u201cThe man who thinks that the average Amer\njean is not honest has no business cheering for\nthe flag,\u201d he sald in closing. \u201cIt is our duty to\nput on our thinking caps and try to devise\nmeans to right the wrong wherever fit exists,\nand not talk so much.\u201d\nReferring to the review of the 2d Battalion\nof Naval Militia which he attended earlier in\nthe evening, Governor Hughes declared that he\nhad seen a splendid exhibition of discipline, and\nthat he noted with pride the work of the naval\nforces under his command.\nWhen Governor Hughes entered the room he\nwas greeted with cheers of the different univer\nsities and many of the guests stood up on their\nchairs and shouted, \u201cOur next President!\u201d The\ncheering lasted for several minutes,\nJustice Townsend Scudder, the toastmaster, in\nintroducing Governor Hughes, said that the\ndiners were not there to make political speeches,\nbut asked the members to listen to the Gov\nernor of the state. This was met with rousing\napplause and more cheers for the \u2018future Pres\n\n\nident.\u201d\nThe boom of \u201cUncie Joe\u201d Cannon for the Presi\ndential- nomination received many boosts from\nRepresentative H. S. Boutell, who spoke on \u201cThe\nShip of State.\u201d If the President is called captain\nof the ship of state, he said, to the Speaker of the\nHouse should be assigned title and honors of the\npilot. He continued:\n\n\nDuring the last five years more legislation of\nermanent, far-reaching value has been enacted\ny Congress than in all the other years since the\nCivil War period. In working out this remedial\nlegislation the President and the Speaker have\nworked in close harmony. ISach has generously\naccorded to the other full recegnition and praise\nof the value of his services.\nIn carrving on in the future the policies of this\nadministration Mr. Cannon as President would sim\npiv be finishing the work which he has been en\nred in during the last five vears in co-operation\nwith President Roosevelt.\nHe paid a high tribute to the success of Presi\ndent Roosevelt's financial policies and vigorously\ndefended the President against the censure that\nhad been directed against him for calling last No\nvember for subscriptions of $50,000,000 for Panama\nbonds and $10,000,000 for the 3 per cent emergency\ncertificates. He declared that there was no simi\nlarity between the situation that induced his action\nand the dilemma that compelled President Cleve\nland to issue $262,000,000 of 5 and 4 per cent bonds.\nSenator Morris Brown spoke of the growth of the\nprinciple of equal rights for all, more recently ex\npressed in \u2018\u2018the celebrated declaration of President\nRoosevelf, when he said: \u2018A square deal for all the\npeople.\u2019 True to this motto, Nebraskans believe\ncertain changes should be made in the tariff sched\nule. He went on:\nThey are protectionists; do not mistake me. But\nprotection as they understand it means reasonable\nschedules. When great corporations obtain a\nmonopoly of our markets and seek to overthrow\nAmerican competitors through a capitalization\nswollen to abnormal proportions and directly due\nto certain schedules, the principle of our motto re\nquires a \u2018revision of those schedules. There is no\nequality in a law that affords any man or corpora\ntion a monopoly; and when a schedule fixed by law\nis found to be responsible for a monopoly, the law\nshould be revised and amended, and, if necessary,\nrepealed. That this revision must be attended\nwith intelligent and patriotic care is conceded. The\npeople seek no indiscriminate revision or destruc\ntion of schedules. They favor no horizontal reduc\ntions.\nOf the interstate commerce law he said:\nBut. whatever of progress has been made, what\never of good has heen accomplished, the work is\nnot yet ended. Equality before the law is not yet\na full realization, nor will it be until, among other\nthings vet to do. the interstate commerce act ia\nso amended that communities, as well as indi\nviduals, shall be denied transportation favors and\nrebates, and reasonable rates shall be established\nfor all products from every fleld and range and\nfactory of this productive country.\nSenator W. E. Borah in his speech paid a high\ntribute to the stability of the American public in\nthe recent financial panic. He said:\nBut this much is certain\u2014thosa scenes of law\njessness, recklessness, frenzy, theft, repentance and\nsuicide were not of the people's making. This\nmuch more is certain, it was the deposits of the\npeople, the small earnings of those of moderate\nmeans, which were used to stay the frighiful dis\naster inaugurated by the daring and recklessness\nof those leading business men.\nIf the masses had become excited, as did these\nfew hundred about the centres of conservative\nbusiness places, there would have been a holocaust\nof indescribable ruin from ocean to ocean.\nT have no patience with that species of artless\ndemagogues which inveighs against the rich be\ncause they are rich, which arraigns corporate\nweanlth honestly obtained and honestly used, which\nwars upon the fruit of industry and frugality. I\nwould smite the uneonscionable adventurer who\nwould raise his parricidal hand against the Con\nstitution whether he marcues under the banner of\nreform or the red flag of anarchy.\nAmong the other speakers were Represantatives\nFrank O. Lowden, from Illinois; Charles Scott,\nfrom Kansas, and (\u2018harles B, Landis, from Indiana.\nBefore the speeches hegan Betas young and old\nbecame undergraduates in spirit once again, and\nbetween vells of colleges from Yale to Virginia and\nweat to California \u201cOld Wooglin and his bobtailed\ndog\u2019 was raised from the shades and brought back\nto earth. Even dignified Senators and Congressmen\n\u201cmade ne bones of carving a canine.\u201d The merry\nmaking reached its height when Mr. Boutell, chair\nman of the committee conducting submarine inves\ntigation at Washington, was greeted with repeated\nstrains of \u201cThere's a hole in the bottom of the\nsea.\u201d\nCongreseman Landis in his speech made men\ntion of the trip of the fleet about the world. He\nsaid it struck him as a peculiar thing that the\npeople whe lived in the interior of the country were\nwilling to support the navy, while from people who\nlived in New York City Congress had been flooded\nwith petitions urging aginst the increase. Follow\ning the Congressman\u2019s speech it was voted to send\nto the United States fleet a telegram including a\npoem which had been written by Robert &E. Mae\nAlatpey, a member of the fraternity.\nThe dinner celebrated the completion of its first\nvear of clubhouse life by the Beia Theta Pi Club.\nMore than a thousand members of this college fra\nternity live mm and around New York. In addition\nto several hundred of them there were delegations\nof undergraduates from Yale, Rutgers, Stevens,\nthe University of Pennsylvania and Iehigh at the\ndinner last night, with the entire chapter from\nColumbia.\nEE er\nRMSE IALS REA AL AAA N BD\u201d DDIMNMDIT\u2122 11I1IRAA YP\" IY\nSVYEr OF SO04h Ty AG A a SY nd CROCE hs The\nnot yet ended. Equality before the law is not yet\na full realization, nor will it be until, among other\nthings vet to do. the interstate commerce act ia\nso amended that communities, as well as indi\nviduals, shall be denied transportation favors and\nrebates, and reasonable rates shall be established\nfor all products from every fleld and range and\nfactory of this productive country.\nSenator W. KE. Borah in his speech paid a high\ntribute to the stability of the American public in\nthe recent financial panic. He said:\nBut this much is certain\u2014thosa scenes of law\njessness, recklessness, frenzy. thelt, repentance and\nsuicide were not of the people's making. This\nmuch more is certain, it was the deposits of the\npeople, the small earnings of those of moderate\nmeans, which were used to stay the frighiful dis\naster inaugurated by the daring and recklessness\nof those leading business men.\nIf the masses had become excited, as did these\nfew hundred about the centres of conservative\nbusiness pl