f other\nstates. When the dinner was finished the Gov\nernor made a short speech, congratulating the\nofficers and men on the opening of their new quar\nters, and telling what was expected of them as\npart of the nation\u2019s military establishment,\nBy this time the battalion was mustered on the\nfloor of the large drill room. The first part of the\nevening's ceremony was the presentation of long\nservice medals to fifteen officers. Without delay\nCaptain Robert P. Forshew, the commander of the\nbattalion, called out the names of the officers who\nwere to receive the medals; and as each one was\ncalled he stepped forward and saluted. A major\nity of tne men who received these medals are Civil\nWar veterans.\nAfter the presentation of the medals the battalion\nwent through the artillery drill. When this drill\nwas about to begin, the Governor and the com\nmittee of officers went to one of the two large\nbridges erected at the east and west ends of the\narmory. These bridges were equipped with con\nning towers and semaphores.\nAfter the artillery drill the battalion quickly\nchanged from white duck te blue and repeated the\ndrill. The Governor watched the work on the floor\nwith keen interest, and also paid close attention\nto the work of the signal men, who were wizswag\ning and working the Areclois system from the\nbridges,\nWhen the drill was finished the Governor left\nthe building for Manhattan. The ceremonies at\nthe armory were followed by a dance.\nANT!-HARMON FIGHT IN CINCINNATI\n[By Telegraph to The Tribune]\n[By Telegraph to The Tribune\nCincinnati, March 21.\u2014The Democratic county\nelection committee adopted a \u201charmony\u201d state\nment this afternoon, which in a manner indorsed\nWw. J. Bryan and ignored Judson Harmon as can\ndidate for President. However, It was decided\n\n\n\n\n0. HAAS BROS.\nTAILORS TO GENTLEWOMEN,\nNOW zo WEST 27TH \u00a7T,,\nFORMERLY OF FIFTH AVE.\nSpecial reduction this week of %h class\nGowns, richly lined, made to order,